  "local_port": 45246,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I have a flight to prague. But In between I have to change flight at Paris! How to do that?",
  "response": "Changing flights in Paris typically involves a few steps, depending on whether you are arriving and departing from the same airport and whether you have a layover or a connection. Here\u2019s a general guide to help you navigate your flight change:\n\n### 1. **Check Your Itinerary:**\n   - Confirm your arrival and departure airports in Paris. The two main airports are Charles de Gaulle Airport (CDG) and Orly Airport (ORY). Make sure you know which one you'll be flying into and out of.\n\n### 2. **Arrival in Paris:**\n   - Upon arrival, follow the signs to baggage claim if you need to collect your luggage. If your bags are checked through to Prague, you can skip this step.\n\n### 3. **Customs and Immigration:**\n   - If you're arriving from a non-Schengen country, you'll need to go through customs and immigration. Ensure you have your travel documents ready.\n\n### 4. **Transfer to Your Next Flight:**\n   - **If you have a layover at the same airport (CDG or ORY):**\n     - Follow signs for \"Connections\" or \"Transfers.\" \n     - Check your boarding gate information on the airport monitors. \n     - Proceed through security if necessary and head to your gate.\n     \n   - **If you\u2019re changing airports:**\n     - You will need to exit the airport, take a taxi, shuttle bus, or public transport (RER train, bus) to the other airport. Allow enough time for travel between airports, as this can take 30-60 minutes or more depending on traffic and the time of day.\n\n### 5. **Check Your Boarding Pass:**\n   - If you haven\u2019t received your boarding pass for the flight to Prague, look for the airline\u2019s check-in desk or use a self-service kiosk to print it.\n\n### 6. **Security Check:**\n   - Be prepared to go through security again before boarding your next flight.\n\n### 7. **Arrive at Your Gate:**\n   - Make your way to the designated gate for your flight to Prague and wait for boarding announcements.\n\n### 8. **Timing:**\n   - Ensure you have enough time between flights. A layover of at least 1.5 to 2 hours is generally recommended for international flights.\n\n### Tips: \n- **Stay Informed:** Keep an eye on flight updates through the airline\u2019s app or website.\n- **Travel Light:** If possible, travel with carry-on luggage to make transfers easier.\n- **Language:** While many people in Paris speak English, having a translation app can be helpful.\n\nIf you have any specific questions or concerns about your flights or the airports, feel free to ask! Safe travels!",
